Here is a sample Powershell script that recursively checks folders to see if their ACLs refer to SIDs which occur only in the SIDHistory of any user or group in the domain:

```powershell
# Function to check if a SID is present in the SIDHistory of any user or group in the domain
function CheckSIDHistory($sid) {
    $domain = [System.DirectoryServices.ActiveDirectory.Domain]::GetCurrentDomain()
    $searcher = [System.DirectoryServices.ActiveDirectory.DirectorySearcher]"(objectSID=$sid)"
    $searcher.SearchRoot = "LDAP://$($domain.Name)"
    $searcher.PropertiesToLoad.Add('objectSIDHistory')
    $result = $searcher.FindOne()

    if ($result.Properties['objectSIDHistory']) {
        # SID is present in SIDHistory
        return $true
    } else {
        return $false
    }
}

# Function to recursively check folders for SIDs in ACLs
function CheckFolderACLs($folderPath) {
    $folder = Get-Acl $folderPath
    $acl = $folder.GetAccessRules($true, $true, [System.Security.Principal.NTAccount])

    foreach ($ace in $acl) {
        foreach ($sid in $ace.IdentityReference.Value) {
            if (-not (CheckSIDHistory $sid)) {
                Write-Host "SID $sid in folder $folderPath does not have SIDHistory in the domain."
            }
        }
    }

    # Recursively check subfolders
    $subfolders = Get-ChildItem $folderPath -Directory
    foreach ($subfolder in $subfolders) {
        CheckFolderACLs $subfolder.FullName
    }
}

# Start checking from the specified root folder
$rootFolder = "C:\Path\To\Root\Folder"
CheckFolderACLs $rootFolder
```

This script will recursively check the specified root folder and all its subfolders for SIDs in ACLs. If a SID is found that does not have a corresponding SIDHistory in the domain, it will output a message indicating the issue.

