Here is an example of a decorator for a Nest.js middleware that checks the `NODE_ENV` variable and calls `next()` if it is `true`, otherwise it returns `false`:

```typescript
import { Injectable, NestMiddleware } from '@nestjs/common';
import { Request, Response } from 'express';

@Injectable()
export class CheckNodeEnvMiddleware implements NestMiddleware {
  use(req: Request, res: Response, next: Function) {
    if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'true') {
      next();
    } else {
      return false;
    }
  }
}
```

You can then use this decorator in your Nest.js application by adding it to a controller or provider using the `@UseMiddleware()` decorator:

```typescript
import { Controller, Get, UseMiddleware } from '@nestjs/common';
import { CheckNodeEnvMiddleware } from './check-node-env.middleware';

@Controller('example')
export class ExampleController {
  @Get()
  @UseMiddleware(CheckNodeEnvMiddleware)
  getExampleData() {
    // Your controller logic here
  }
}
```

This will ensure that the `CheckNodeEnvMiddleware` is executed before the `getExampleData()` method is called, and it will check the `NODE_ENV` variable and either call `next()` or return `false` based on its value.

