Here is a simple React utility function that removes widows from a given text:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

const removeWidows = (text) => {
  const words = text.split(' ');
  let result = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < words.length - 1; i++) {
    if (words[i].trim() === '' || words[i + 1].trim() === '') {
      continue;
    }

    result.push(words[i]);

    if (i === words.length - 2) {
      result.push(words[i + 1]);
    } else if (
      words[i].endsWith('.') ||
      words[i].endsWith(',') ||
      words[i].endsWith(':') ||
      words[i].endsWith(';') ||
      words[i].endsWith('!') ||
      words[i].endsWith('?')
    ) {
      result.push(<>&nbsp;</>);
    }
  }

  return result.join(' ');
};

const TextComponent = ({ text }) => {
  const formattedText = removeWidows(text);

  return <p>{formattedText}</p>;
};

export default TextComponent;
```

In this utility function, we first split the input text into an array of words using the `split` method. We then iterate through the words array and check if the current word and the next word are not empty. If they are not empty, we add the current word to the result array. If the current word ends with certain punctuation marks like '.', ',', ':', ';', '!', or '?', we add a non-breaking space (`&nbsp;`) to prevent widows.

Finally, we join the result array back into a string and return it. You can use this `removeWidows` function in a `TextComponent` to display text without widows.

